{"title_page": "John Law (minister)", "text_new": "{{Use British English|date=April 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2019}}\n{{Infobox Christian leader\n| type             = \n| honorific_prefix = \n| name             = John Law\n| honorific_suffix = \n| title            = \n| image            = Charnel-house in Greyfriars Kirkyard - geograph.org.uk - 1302432.jpg\n| image_size       = \n| alt              = \n| caption          = John Law's tomb\n| native_name      = \n| native_name_lang = \n| church           = \n| archdiocese      = \n| province         = \n| metropolis       = \n| diocese          = \n| see              = \n| elected          = <!-- or | appointed = -->\n| term             = <!-- or term_start / term_end -->\n| quashed          = <!-- or | retired = -->\n| predecessor      = \n| successor        = \n| opposed          = \n| other_post       = \n<!---------- Orders ---------->\n| ordination       = \n| ordained_by      = \n| consecration     = \n| consecrated_by   = \n| cardinal         = \n| created_cardinal_by =\n| rank             = \n| laicized         = \n<!---------- Personal details ---------->\n| birth_name       = \n| birth_date       = 1632\n| birth_place      = Inchinnan\n| death_date       = {{Death date|1712|12|26}}\n| death_place      = Edinburgh\n| buried           = Greyfriars Kirkyard\n| resting_place_coordinates = \n| nationality      = Scottish\n| religion         = Presbyterian\n| residence        = \n| parents          = \n| spouse           = <!-- or | partner = -->\n| children         = \n| occupation       = \n| profession       = <!-- or | previous_post = -->\n| education        =\n| alma_mater       = \n| motto            = \n| signature        = \n| signature_alt    = \n| coat_of_arms     = \n| coat_of_arms_alt = \n<!---------- Other ---------->\n| module           = \n| module2          = \n| other            = \n}}\n[[File:The-tolbooth-and-st-giles-cathedral-edinburgh.jpg|thumb|The Tolbooth (a Covenanting prison) and St. Giles Cathedral, Edinburgh]]\n'''John Law''' was a 17th-century Presbyterian minister from [[Scotland]]. He became a moderator and was a prisoner on the Bass Rock.<ref name=\"Fasti1\">{{cite book |last1=Scott |first1=Hew |title=Fasti ecclesiae scoticanae; the succession of ministers in the Church of Scotland from the reformation |date=1915 |publisher=Edinburgh: Oliver and Boyd |pages=[https://archive.org/details/fastiecclesiaesc01scot/page/66 66] |volume=1 |url=https://archive.org/details/fastiecclesiaesc01scot |accessdate=16 March 2019}}{{PD-notice}}</ref>\n\nLaw was born in 1632, the son of Thomas Law, minister of Inchinnan. Like [[John Spreul (apothecary)|John Spreul]] he began life as an [[apothecary]]. He graduated with an M.A. from the [[University of Glasgow]] in 1653. He was ordained to be the minister of [[Campsie, East Dunbartonshire|Campsie]] in 1656. He was deprived of this charge in 1662 but later restored in 1678. He was again deprived on account of the Test in 1681. He was called to the High Church 22 July 1689. He was appointed to the charge 20 April 1692 and confirmed by the town council 24 July 1689. He was a member of the General Assemblies in 1690 and 1692 and was elected [[Moderator of the General Assembly of the Church of Scotland|Moderator]] in 1694. He was appointed [[almoner]] to His Majesty on 2 October 1700 (P. S. Reg. Eng., v., 390). He demitted his charge or retired on 26 November 1707 and died 26 December 1712.<ref name=\"Fasti1\"/>\n\nHe was interred on the [[Bass Rock]] from April 1679 until July 1679.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Dickson |first1=John |title=Emeralds chased in Gold; or, the Islands of the Forth: their story, ancient and modern. [With illustrations.] |date=1899 |publisher=Oliphant, Anderson & Ferrier |location=Edinburgh and London |pages=219\u2013220 |url=http://access.bl.uk/item/viewer/ark:/81055/vdc_000000058DB2#?c=0&m=0&s=0&cv=248&xywh=-478%2C-1%2C3793%2C2303&r=0|accessdate=3 March 2019}}{{PD-notice}}</ref> His brother was the minister of East Kilpatrick.<ref>{{cite book |title=Extracts from the Records of the Old Tolbooth from The book of the Old Edinburgh Club |date=1913 |publisher=Edinburgh : The Club |page=[https://archive.org/details/bookofoldedinbur6191olde/page/126 126] |edition=Vol. 6 |url=https://archive.org/details/bookofoldedinbur6191olde |accessdate=20 March 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=Monteith |first1=Robert |title=Collection of epitaphs and monumental inscriptions, chiefly in Scotland |date=1834 |publisher=Glasgow: Printed for D. Macvean |page=[https://archive.org/details/collectionepita00macvgoog/page/n303 293] |url=https://archive.org/details/collectionepita00macvgoog |accessdate=15 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Early ministry==\nJohn Law, born around 1632, graduated with a Master of Arts degree from [[University of Glasgow|Glasgow University]] allowing him to be known as Mr. John Law.<ref>{{cite book |last1=M'Crie |first1=Thomas, D.D. the younger |title=The Bass rock: Its civil and ecclesiastic history |date=1847 |publisher=J. Greig & Son |location=Edinburgh |pages=[https://archive.org/details/bassrockitscivil00mcri/page/n435 276]\u2013287 |url=https://archive.org/details/bassrockitscivil00mcri |accessdate=11 February 2019}}</ref>   He was ordained by the Protesters to be minister of [[Campsie, Stirlingshire|Campsie]] in 1656. He was deprived by an Act of Parliament on 11 June, and Decreet of Privy Council 1 October 1662.<ref name=\"Fasti\">{{cite book |last1=Scott |first1=Hew |authorlink=Hew Scott|title=Fasti ecclesiae scoticanae; the succession of ministers in the Church of Scotland from the reformation |date=1920 |publisher=Edinburgh: Oliver and Boyd |page=[https://archive.org/details/fastiecclesiasco03scotuoft/page/n385 376] |volume=3 |url=https://archive.org/details/fastiecclesiasco03scotuoft |accessdate=15 March 2019}}{{PD-notice}}</ref> Law for the next eight years conducted [[conventicles]] \u2014 often at great risk to himself \u2014 in the west of [[Stirlingshire]], about [[Kippen]], [[Gargunnock]], and [[Menteith]]. Under the \"Indulgence Act\" he was allowed to exercise the functions of the ministry in the parish of [[Irvine, North Ayrshire|Irvine]] in 1672, but declined, and as he did not appear before the council when called, 12 March 1673, they ordered his apprehension, 4 June 1674.<ref name=\"Fasti\"/> However, he did not con\ufb01ne himself to these parts; and, accordingly, a warrant was issued for his apprehension. He was accused at the [[Diocesan Synod]], 22 October, of holding conventicles at Kippen.<ref name=\"Fasti\"/> Captured and taken to the Tolbooth of Edinburgh, Law was brought before \"My Lords\" but discharged upon a security of \ufb01ve thousand merks to \"live orderly \"; or, in default thereof, to be treated as a \"seditious\" person. This was in 1674. But he was no sooner set at liberty than he entered again into all the enthusiasm of conventicles and managed, for \ufb01ve years, to elude the state's control. He was [[put to the horn]] on 7 December 1676.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Wodrow |first1=Robert |title=The history of the sufferings of the Church of Scotland from the Restoration to the Revolution |date=1832 |publisher=Blackie |location=Glasgow |page=[https://archive.org/details/thehistoryofthes02wodruoft/page/n348 336] |volume= 2 |url=https://archive.org/details/thehistoryofthes02wodruoft |accessdate=23 February 2019}}</ref>\n\nA meeting-house built for him in the parish in 1678 was demolished by order of the council.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Wodrow |first1=Robert |title=The history of the sufferings of the Church of Scotland from the Restoration to the Revolution |date=1832 |publisher=Blackie |location=Glasgow |page=[https://archive.org/details/thehistoryofthes02wodruoft/page/n431 418] |edition=Vol 2 |url=https://archive.org/details/thehistoryofthes02wodruoft |accessdate=23 February 2019}}</ref>  About the beginning of 1679 he was arrested, in the house of the laird of Kincaid, while on his way to visit his dying wife. (Mrs. Law seems to have recovered from her dangerous illness at that time, as the date of her death, marked on the tombstone in Old Greyfriars, was 8 November 1703.) He was sent prisoner to the [[Bass Rock]] in 1679, for \"invading several pulpits and presuming to ordain persons to the ministry\" but was released after three months on finding caution to appear when called and under a bond of one thousand merks.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Crichton |first1=Andrew |title=Memoirs of the Rev. John Blackader |date=1826 |publisher=Charles Tait |location=London |page=[https://archive.org/details/memoirsrevjohnb00blacgoog/page/n361 344] |edition=2nd |url=https://archive.org/details/memoirsrevjohnb00blacgoog |accessdate=15 March 2019}}</ref>\n<ref>{{cite book |last1=Porteous |first1=James Moir |title=The Scottish Patmos. A standing testimony to patriotic Christian devotion |date=1881 |publisher=J. and R. Parlane |location=Paisley |pages=[https://archive.org/details/scottishpatmosa00portgoog/page/n51 48]\u201349 |url=https://archive.org/details/scottishpatmosa00portgoog |accessdate=3 March 2019}}{{PD-notice}}</ref> He was deprived in 1681, probably on account of the Test was restored by Act of Parliament 25 April 1690, but having been called to the High Kirk, Edinburgh, accepted that charge.<ref name=\"Fasti\"/><ref>{{cite book |last1=Bedford |first1=Frederick William |last2=Steven |first2=William |title=History of George Heriot's Hospital |date=1859 |publisher=Bell & Bradfute |page=[https://archive.org/details/historygeorgehe00stevgoog/page/n394 356] |url=https://archive.org/details/historygeorgehe00stevgoog |accessdate=20 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n==After the Revolutionary Settlement==\nAfter the [[Glorious Revolution|Revolution]] he became minister of the St. Giles', Edinburgh.<ref name=\"Fasti1\"/>\n\nLaw died in December 1712, at the advanced age of eighty years, and was buried in the [[Greyfriars Kirkyard|churchyard of Old Greyfriars]]. His Wife, Isabella Cunninghame, \"noted for true holiness,\" was interred in the same place, on 8 November 1703, in her 70th year.<ref name=\"Edinburgh: J. M. Miller\">{{cite book |last1=Brown |first1=James |title=The epitaphs and monumental inscriptions in Greyfriars Churchyard, Edinburgh. Collected by James Brown ... with an introd. and notes. |date=1867 |publisher=Edinburgh: J. M. Miller |page=5|url=https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=hvd.hn3n2m;view=1up;seq=103 |accessdate=15 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Family life==\nHe married Isabella (died 8 November 1703, aged 70), who was the daughter of Robert Cunningham, minister of Holywood, Ireland, and had issue \u2014 William, professor of moral philosophy in the [[University of Edinburgh]], founder of the family of Law of Elvingston, East Lothian.<ref name=\"Fasti1\"/>\n[[File:Charnel-house in Greyfriars Kirkyard - geograph.org.uk - 1302432.jpg|thumb|John Law's vault<ref>{{cite web |title=John Law |url=https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/80509466/john-law |website=Find A Grave|accessdate=19 July 2019 |ref=Memorial ID: 80509466}}</ref>]]\nWilliam built a tomb for his parents in Greyfriars Kirkyard. The inscription<ref name=\"Edinburgh: J. M. Miller\"/> reads:\n:Memoriae optimorum parentum, D. Joannis Law, ecclesiae apud Edinensis pastoris prudentissimi, vigilantis- simi, purioris religionis studio & pietate non fucata insignis; et Isabella Cuninghame, conjugis amantissimae, vera sanctitate & placidi ac sedati animi ornamento conspicuae; qui mortalitatem exuerunt, ad immortalis vitae gaudia nitentes; ille 26 die Decembris, anno Dom. 1712, aetatis suae 80 ; haec 8 die Novembris, anno Dom. 1703, aetatis suae 70 ; hoc monumentum sacrum esse voluit Gulielmus Law, filius.\n\n:To the memory of his most excellent parents, Mr John Law, a most prudent and vigilant pastor of the Church at Edinburgh, distinguished by his zeal for pure religion, and his unfeigned piety ; and Isabella Cuninghame, his affectionate wife, noted for true holiness, and the ornament of a meek and quiet spirit, who, pressing towards the joys of eternal life, laid aside mortality, \u2014 the former on the 26th December A.d. 1712, in his 80th year ; the latter on the 8th November A.d. 1703, in her 70th year,\u2014 this monument was dedicated by William Law, their son. \u2014 M.]\n\n==Bibliography==\n*Edin. Counc, Guild, Reg. (Bur.) ; \n*Tombst. ; \n*Monteith's Mort., ii. ; \n*Wodrow's Anal., iii. ; \n*Peterkin's Const.\n*Leven and Melv. Pap.<ref name=\"Fasti1\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n{{Bass Rock Prisoners of Conscience}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Law, John}}\n[[Category:Scottish clergy]]\n[[Category:17th-century Presbyterian ministers]]\n[[Category:Covenanters]]\n[[Category:1712 deaths]]\n[[Category:Scottish prisoners and detainees]]\n[[Category:1632 births]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use British English|date=April 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2019}}\n{{Infobox Christian leader\n| type             = \n| honorific_prefix = \n| name             = John Law\n| honorific_suffix = \n| title            = \n| image            = Charnel-house in Greyfriars Kirkyard - geograph.org.uk - 1302432.jpg\n| image_size       = \n| alt              = \n| caption          = John Law's tomb\n| native_name      = \n| native_name_lang = \n| church           = \n| archdiocese      = \n| province         = \n| metropolis       = \n| diocese          = \n| see              = \n| elected          = <!-- or | appointed = -->\n| term             = <!-- or term_start / term_end -->\n| quashed          = <!-- or | retired = -->\n| predecessor      = \n| successor        = \n| opposed          = \n| other_post       = \n<!---------- Orders ---------->\n| ordination       = \n| ordained_by      = \n| consecration     = \n| consecrated_by   = \n| cardinal         = \n| created_cardinal_by =\n| rank             = \n| laicized         = \n<!---------- Personal details ---------->\n| birth_name       = \n| birth_date       = 1632\n| birth_place      = Inchinnan\n| death_date       = {{Death date|1712|12|26}}\n| death_place      = Edinburgh\n| buried           = Greyfriars Kirkyard\n| resting_place_coordinates = \n| nationality      = Scottish\n| religion         = Presbyterian\n| residence        = \n| parents          = \n| spouse           = <!-- or | partner = -->\n| children         = \n| occupation       = \n| profession       = <!-- or | previous_post = -->\n| education        =\n| alma_mater       = \n| motto            = \n| signature        = \n| signature_alt    = \n| coat_of_arms     = \n| coat_of_arms_alt = \n<!---------- Other ---------->\n| module           = \n| module2          = \n| other            = \n}}\n[[File:The-tolbooth-and-st-giles-cathedral-edinburgh.jpg|thumb|The Tolbooth (a Covenanting prison) and St. Giles Cathedral, Edinburgh]]\n'''John Law''' was a 17th century Presbyterian minister from [[Scotland]]. He became a Moderator and was a prisoner on the Bass Rock.<ref name=\"Fasti1\">{{cite book |last1=Scott |first1=Hew |title=Fasti ecclesiae scoticanae; the succession of ministers in the Church of Scotland from the reformation |date=1915 |publisher=Edinburgh: Oliver and Boyd |pages=[https://archive.org/details/fastiecclesiaesc01scot/page/66 66] |volume=1 |url=https://archive.org/details/fastiecclesiaesc01scot |accessdate=16 March 2019}}{{PD-notice}}</ref>\n\nJohn Law was born in 1632, the son of Thomas Law, minister of Inchinnan. Like [[John Spreul (apothecary)|John Spreul]] he began life as an [[apothecary]]. He graduated with an M.A. from the [[University of Glasgow]] in 1653. He was ordained to be the minister of [[Campsie, East Dunbartonshire|Campsie]] in 1656. He was deprived of this charge in 1662 but later restored in 1678. He was again deprived on account of the Test in 1681. He was called to the High Church 22 July 1689. He was appointed to the charge 20 April 1692 and confirmed by the Town Council 24 July 1689. He was a member of the General Assemblies in 1690 and 1692 and was elected [[Moderator of the General Assembly of the Church of Scotland|Moderator]] in 1694. He was appointed [[Almoner]] to His Majesty on 2 October 1700 (P. S. Reg. Eng., v., 390). He demitted his charge or retired on 26 November 1707 and died 26 December 1712.<ref name=\"Fasti1\"/>\n\nHe was interred on the [[Bass Rock]] from April, 1679 until July, 1679.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Dickson |first1=John |title=Emeralds chased in Gold; or, the Islands of the Forth: their story, ancient and modern. [With illustrations.] |date=1899 |publisher=Oliphant, Anderson & Ferrier |location=Edinburgh and London |pages=219\u2013220 |url=http://access.bl.uk/item/viewer/ark:/81055/vdc_000000058DB2#?c=0&m=0&s=0&cv=248&xywh=-478%2C-1%2C3793%2C2303&r=0|accessdate=3 March 2019}}{{PD-notice}}</ref> His brother was the minister of East Kilpatrick.<ref>{{cite book |title=Extracts from the Records of the Old Tolbooth from The book of the Old Edinburgh Club |date=1913 |publisher=Edinburgh : The Club |page=[https://archive.org/details/bookofoldedinbur6191olde/page/126 126] |edition=Vol. 6 |url=https://archive.org/details/bookofoldedinbur6191olde |accessdate=20 March 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=Monteith |first1=Robert |title=Collection of epitaphs and monumental inscriptions, chiefly in Scotland |date=1834 |publisher=Glasgow: Printed for D. Macvean |page=[https://archive.org/details/collectionepita00macvgoog/page/n303 293] |url=https://archive.org/details/collectionepita00macvgoog |accessdate=15 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Early ministry==\nJohn Law, born around 1632, graduated with a Master of Arts degree from [[University of Glasgow|Glasgow University]] allowing him to be known as Mr. John Law.<ref>{{cite book |last1=M'Crie |first1=Thomas, D.D. the younger |title=The Bass rock: Its civil and ecclesiastic history |date=1847 |publisher=J. Greig & Son |location=Edinburgh |pages=[https://archive.org/details/bassrockitscivil00mcri/page/n435 276]\u2013287 |url=https://archive.org/details/bassrockitscivil00mcri |accessdate=11 February 2019}}</ref>   He was ordained by the Protesters to be minister of [[Campsie, Stirlingshire|Campsie]] in 1656. He was deprived by an Act of Parliament on 11 June, and Decreet of Privy Council 1 October 1662.<ref name=\"Fasti\">{{cite book |last1=Scott |first1=Hew |authorlink=Hew Scott|title=Fasti ecclesiae scoticanae; the succession of ministers in the Church of Scotland from the reformation |date=1920 |publisher=Edinburgh: Oliver and Boyd |page=[https://archive.org/details/fastiecclesiasco03scotuoft/page/n385 376] |volume=3 |url=https://archive.org/details/fastiecclesiasco03scotuoft |accessdate=15 March 2019}}{{PD-notice}}</ref> Law for the next eight years conducted [[conventicles]] \u2014 often at great risk to himself \u2014 in the west of [[Stirlingshire]], about [[Kippen]], [[Gargunnock]], and [[Menteith]]. Under the \"Indulgence Act \" he was allowed to exercise the functions of the ministry in the parish of [[Irvine, North Ayrshire|Irvine]] in 1672, but declined, and as he did not appear before the Council when called, 12 March 1673, they ordered his apprehension, 4 June 1674.<ref name=\"Fasti\"/> However, he did not con\ufb01ne himself to these parts; and, accordingly, a warrant was issued for his apprehension. He was accused at the [[Diocesan Synod]], 22 October, of holding conventicles at Kippen.<ref name=\"Fasti\"/> Captured and taken to the Tolbooth of Edinburgh, Law was brought before \"My Lords\" but discharged upon a security of \ufb01ve thousand merks to \"live orderly \"; or, in default thereof, to be treated as a \"seditious\" person. This was in 1674. But he was no sooner set at liberty than he entered again into all the enthusiasm of conventicles and managed, for \ufb01ve years, to elude the state's control. He was [[put to the horn]] on 7 December 1676.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Wodrow |first1=Robert |title=The history of the sufferings of the Church of Scotland from the Restoration to the Revolution |date=1832 |publisher=Blackie |location=Glasgow |page=[https://archive.org/details/thehistoryofthes02wodruoft/page/n348 336] |volume= 2 |url=https://archive.org/details/thehistoryofthes02wodruoft |accessdate=23 February 2019}}</ref>\n\nA meeting-house built for him in the parish in 1678 was demolished by order of the Council.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Wodrow |first1=Robert |title=The history of the sufferings of the Church of Scotland from the Restoration to the Revolution |date=1832 |publisher=Blackie |location=Glasgow |page=[https://archive.org/details/thehistoryofthes02wodruoft/page/n431 418] |edition=Vol 2 |url=https://archive.org/details/thehistoryofthes02wodruoft |accessdate=23 February 2019}}</ref>  About the beginning of 1679 he was arrested, in the house of the laird of Kincaid, while on his way to visit his dying wife. (Mrs. Law seems to have recovered from her dangerous illness at that time, as the date of her death, marked on the tombstone in Old Greyfriars, was 8 November 1703.) He was sent prisoner to the [[Bass Rock]] in 1679, for \"invading several pulpits and presuming to ordain persons to the ministry\" but was released after three months on finding caution to appear when called and under a bond of one thousand merks.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Crichton |first1=Andrew |title=Memoirs of the Rev. John Blackader |date=1826 |publisher=Charles Tait |location=London |page=[https://archive.org/details/memoirsrevjohnb00blacgoog/page/n361 344] |edition=2nd |url=https://archive.org/details/memoirsrevjohnb00blacgoog |accessdate=15 March 2019}}</ref>\n<ref>{{cite book |last1=Porteous |first1=James Moir |title=The Scottish Patmos. A standing testimony to patriotic Christian devotion |date=1881 |publisher=J. and R. Parlane |location=Paisley |pages=[https://archive.org/details/scottishpatmosa00portgoog/page/n51 48]\u201349 |url=https://archive.org/details/scottishpatmosa00portgoog |accessdate=3 March 2019}}{{PD-notice}}</ref> He was deprived in 1681, probably on account of the Test was restored by Act of Parliament 25 April 1690, but having been called to the High Kirk, Edinburgh, accepted that charge.<ref name=\"Fasti\"/><ref>{{cite book |last1=Bedford |first1=Frederick William |last2=Steven |first2=William |title=History of George Heriot's Hospital |date=1859 |publisher=Bell & Bradfute |page=[https://archive.org/details/historygeorgehe00stevgoog/page/n394 356] |url=https://archive.org/details/historygeorgehe00stevgoog |accessdate=20 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n==After the Revolutionary Settlement==\nAfter the [[Glorious Revolution|Revolution]] he became minister of the St. Giles', Edinburgh.<ref name=\"Fasti1\"/>\n\nLaw died in December 1712, at the advanced age of eighty years, and was buried in the [[Greyfriars Kirkyard|churchyard of Old Greyfriars]]. His Wife, Isabella Cunninghame, \"noted for true holiness,\" was interred in the same place, on 8 November 1703, in her 70th year.<ref name=\"Edinburgh: J. M. Miller\">{{cite book |last1=Brown |first1=James |title=The epitaphs and monumental inscriptions in Greyfriars Churchyard, Edinburgh. Collected by James Brown ... with an introd. and notes. |date=1867 |publisher=Edinburgh: J. M. Miller |page=5|url=https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=hvd.hn3n2m;view=1up;seq=103 |accessdate=15 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Family life==\nHe married Isabella (died 8 November 1703, aged 70), who was the daughter of Robert Cunningham, minister of Holywood, Ireland, and had issue \u2014 William, Professor of Moral Philosophy in the [[University of Edinburgh]], founder of the family of Law of Elvingston, East Lothian.<ref name=\"Fasti1\"/>\n[[File:Charnel-house in Greyfriars Kirkyard - geograph.org.uk - 1302432.jpg|thumb|John Law's vault<ref>{{cite web |title=John Law |url=https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/80509466/john-law |website=Find A Grave|accessdate=19 July 2019 |ref=Memorial ID: 80509466}}</ref>]]\nWilliam built a tomb for his parents in Greyfriars Kirkyard. The inscription<ref name=\"Edinburgh: J. M. Miller\"/> reads:\n:Memoriae optimorum parentum, D. Joannis Law, ecclesiae apud Edinensis pastoris prudentissimi, vigilantis- simi, purioris religionis studio & pietate non fucata insignis; et Isabella Cuninghame, conjugis amantissimae, vera sanctitate & placidi ac sedati animi ornamento conspicuae; qui mortalitatem exuerunt, ad immortalis vitae gaudia nitentes; ille 26 die Decembris, anno Dom. 1712, aetatis suae 80 ; haec 8 die Novembris, anno Dom. 1703, aetatis suae 70 ; hoc monumentum sacrum esse voluit Gulielmus Law, filius.\n\n:To the memory of his most excellent parents, Mr John Law, a most prudent and vigilant pastor of the Church at Edinburgh, distinguished by his zeal for pure religion, and his unfeigned piety ; and Isabella Cuninghame, his affectionate wife, noted for true holiness, and the ornament of a meek and quiet spirit, who, pressing towards the joys of eternal life, laid aside mortality, \u2014 the former on the 26th December A.d. 1712, in his 80th year ; the latter on the 8th November A.d. 1703, in her 70th year,\u2014 this monument was dedicated by William Law, their son. \u2014 M.]\n\n==Bibliography==\n*Edin. Counc, Guild, Reg. (Bur.) ; \n*Tombst. ; \n*Monteith's Mort., ii. ; \n*Wodrow's Anal., iii. ; \n*Peterkin's Const.\n*Leven and Melv. Pap.<ref name=\"Fasti1\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n{{Bass Rock Prisoners of Conscience}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Law, John}}\n[[Category:Scottish clergy]]\n[[Category:17th-century Presbyterian ministers]]\n[[Category:Covenanters]]\n[[Category:1712 deaths]]\n[[Category:Scottish prisoners and detainees]]\n[[Category:1632 births]]\n", "name_user": "Chris the speller", "label": "safe", "comment": "cap, punct", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_Law_(minister)"}
{"title_page": "Stanley Johnson (writer)", "text_new": "{{other people|Stanley Johnson}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2018}}\n{{Use British English|date=February 2015}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name        = Stanley Johnson\n|image       = Stanleyjohnson.jpg\n|office      = [[Member of the European Parliament]]<br>for [[Wight and Hampshire East (European Parliament constituency)|Wight and Hampshire East]]\n|term_start  = 7 June 1979\n|term_end    = 14 June 1984\n|predecessor = Constituency established\n|successor   = [[Richard Simmonds]]\n|birth_name  = Stanley Patrick Johnson\n|birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1940|8|18|df=y}}\n|birth_place = [[Penzance]], [[Cornwall]], England\n|death_date  = \n|death_place = \n|party       = [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]]\n|spouse      = {{Unbulleted list|{{marriage|[[Charlotte Johnson Wahl|Charlotte Fawcett]]<br>|1963|1979|end=div}}|{{marriage|Jennifer Kidd<br>|1981}}}}\n|children    = {{hlist|[[Boris Johnson|Boris]]|[[Rachel Johnson|Rachel]]|Leo|[[Jo Johnson|Jo]]|Julia|Maximilian}}\n|relatives   = [[Ali Kemal]] (grandfather)\n|alma_mater  = [[Exeter College, Oxford]]\n|module      = {{Listen\n|embed       = yes\n|title       = Johnson's voice \n|filename    = Stanley Johnson - Profile - 4 August 2012.flac\n|type        = speech\n|description = ''[[Desert Island Discs]]'', 18 May 2008 from the BBC programme Profile, 4 August 2012<ref name=\"BBC-b01ldg65\">{{cite episode |title=Stanley Johnson |series=Profile |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b01ldg65 |accessdate=18 January 2014 |station=BBC Radio 4 |date=4 August 2012}}</ref>}}\n}}\n'''Stanley Patrick Johnson''' (born 18 August 1940) is a [[United Kingdom|British]] author<ref>{{cite news |title=Family of influence behind Boris Johnson |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/london-mayor-election/mayor-of-london/1924866/London-mayor-elections-2008-Family-of-influence-behind-Boris-Johnson.html |accessdate=23 July 2019 |publisher=UK Daily Telegraph |date=3 May 2008}}</ref> and former politician. He is also the father of the current British Prime Minister [[Boris Johnson]]. He has written books on environmental and population issues. He was a [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] [[Member of the European Parliament|MEP]] for [[Wight and Hampshire East (European Parliament constituency)|Wight and Hampshire East]] from 1979 to 1984 and is a former employee of the [[World Bank]] and the [[European Commission]].\n\nHis six children include [[Boris Johnson]], who is the [[Leader of the Conservative Party (UK)|Leader of the Conservative Party]] and [[Prime Minister of the United Kingdom]], and former [[Mayor of London]]; [[Jo Johnson]], former MP for [[Orpington (UK Parliament constituency)|Orpington]] and Minister of State for Universities, Science, Research and Innovation; and [[Rachel Johnson]], an editor, journalist, television presenter and author.\n\n==Origins and early life==\nStanley Johnson was born in 1940 in [[Penzance]], Cornwall, the son of Osman Kemal (later Wilfred Johnson) and Irene Williams (daughter of Stanley Fred Williams of [[Bromley]], [[Kent]], and Marie Louise [[Pfeffel family|de Pfeffel]]).<ref>\"Deaths\", ''[[The Times]]'', p. 1, 1 December 1944.</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/world/europe/istanbul-letter-lunch-with-boris-johnson-s-turkish-cousin-1.2650967 |title=Istanbul Letter: Lunch with Boris Johnson\u2019s Turkish cousin |first=Lorraine Mallinder in |last=Istanbul |website=The Irish Times |accessdate=13 June 2019}}</ref> His paternal grandfather, [[Ali Kemal]] Bey, one of the last interior ministers of the [[Ottoman Empire]] government, was assassinated in 1922 during the [[Turkish War of Independence]]. Stanley's father was born in 1909 in [[Bournemouth]], in Hampshire, and his birth was registered as Osman Ali Wilfred Kemal.<ref>Register of Births for the Christchurch Registration District, volume 2b (Dec 1909), p. 621: \"KEMAL, Osman Wilfred\"</ref> Osman's Anglo-Swiss mother Winifred Brun died shortly after giving birth.<ref>Register of Deaths for the Christchurch Registration District, volume 2b (Dec 1909), p. 417: \"KEMAL, Winifred\"</ref> Ali Kemal returned to [[Turkey]] in 1912, whereafter Osman Wilfred and his sister Selma were brought up by their English grandmother, Margaret Brun, and took her maiden name, Johnson, Stanley's father therefore becoming simply Wilfred Johnson.<ref>{{cite web |title=Istanbul Letter: Lunch with Boris Johnson's Turkish cousin |url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/world/europe/istanbul-letter-lunch-with-boris-johnson-s-turkish-cousin-1.2650967 |year=2016 |newspaper=The Irish Times}}</ref>\n\nStanley Johnson's maternal grandmother's parents were Hubert [[Freiherr]] von Pfeffel (born in [[Munich]] on 8 December 1843) and his wife H\u00e9l\u00e8ne [[Jules Arnous de Rivi\u00e8re|Arnous-Rivi\u00e8re]] (born on 14 January 1862). Hubert von Pfeffel was the son of Karl Freiherr von Pfeffel (born in [[Dresden]] on 22 November 1811; died in Munich on 25 January 1890) by his marriage in [[Augsburg]] on 16 February 1836 to Karolina von Rothenburg (born in [[Frankfurt]] on 28 November 1805; died in Frankfurt on 13 February 1872), herself said to be the [[Legitimacy (family law)|illegitimate]], natural daughter of [[Prince Paul of W\u00fcrttemberg]] by Friederike Porth.\n\nJohnson attended [[Sherborne School]], Dorset. While still an undergraduate reading [[Literae Humaniores|Greats]] at [[Exeter College, Oxford|Exeter College]], [[Oxford University|Oxford]], he took part in the Marco Polo Expedition with [[Tim Severin]] and [[Michael de Larrabeiti]], travelling on a motorcycle and sidecar from [[Oxford]] to [[Venice]] and on to India and Afghanistan. The adventure led to the publication of Severin's 1964 book ''Tracking Marco Polo'', with photographs by de Larrabeiti.\n\n==Work and interests==\nHe has previously worked at the [[World Bank Group|World Bank]], has a great interest in the environment and was the Head of Prevention of Pollution Division at the [[European Commission]] from 1973 to 1979. He is a trustee of the Gorilla Organisation and a board member of [[Plantlife International]]. In 1983 he received the [[RSPCA]] Richard Martin Award for Outstanding Services to animal welfare, and in 1984 he received the [[Greenpeace]] Award for Outstanding Services to the Environment. He is an ambassador for the UNEP [[Convention on the Conservation of Migratory Species of Wild Animals]] based in [[Bonn]], Germany.\n\nHe has published a number of books dealing with environmental issues and nine novels, including ''[[The Commissioner (film)|The Commissioner]]'', which was made into a 1998 film starring [[John Hurt]]. In 1962 he won the [[Newdigate Prize]] for Poetry.\n\n==Recent activities==\nAt the [[2005 United Kingdom general election|2005 general election]], Johnson stood for the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]] in the constituency of [[Teignbridge (UK Parliament constituency)|Teignbridge]]. He came second behind [[Richard Younger-Ross]] of the [[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrats]].\n\nFor a time, starting on 26 May 2005, he wrote a weekly column for the ''G2'' section of ''[[The Guardian]]'', and continues to write for various newspapers and magazines, often on environmental topics (see Stanley Johnson personal site below for details). He was one of the first regular hosts of the late night discussion programme ''The Last Word'' on Channel 4's [[More4]] channel, and made an appearance on ''[[Have I Got News For You]]'' on 7 May 2004.{{citation needed|date=March 2018}}\n\nOn 5 May 2008, it was reported that Johnson hoped to be selected to contest his son [[Boris Johnson|Boris]]'s parliamentary seat of [[Henley (UK Parliament constituency)|Henley]] for the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/pages/live/articles/news/news.html?in_article_id=563847&in_page_id=1770&ct=5 |title=Bank holiday Boris promises to work 'night and day' as father eyes his Commons seat |newspaper=[[Daily Mail]] |date=5 May 2008 |accessdate=5 May 2008}}</ref>{{unreliable source?|date=May 2018}} However, on 29 May it was reported that the local Conservative party had chosen three local people as possible candidates<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/oxfordshire/7425090.stm |title=Johnson's father in election snub |publisher=[[BBC News]] |date=29 May 2008 |accessdate=31 May 2008}}</ref> and on 30 May, local councillor [[John Howell (politician)|John Howell]] was selected to fight the by-election.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/oxfordshire/7428812.stm |title=Tory candidate chosen for Henley |publisher=BBC News |date=30 May 2008 |accessdate=31 May 2008}}</ref>\n\nHe has written a memoir, ''Stanley I Presume'', which was published in March 2009.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.stanleyjohnson.com/books/ |title=Stanley Johnson's website - Books page}}</ref>\n\nHaving supported the Remain campaign during the [[2016 United Kingdom European Union membership referendum|2016 European Union membership referendum]], in October 2017 he came out in support of the United Kingdom leaving the European Union, stating that \"the time has come to bail out\" and cited the approach and attitude of the [[European Commission]] [[President of the European Commission|president]] [[Jean-Claude Juncker]] as a major factor in his change of mind. He added that argument and debate over the length or detail of any transition or implementation period is expected but the ultimate \"end-state\" of the UK leaving the European Union is decided.<ref>{{cite news |last=Perring |first=Rebecca |date=6 October 2017 |title=Boris Johnson\u2019s Remainer dad now backs Brexit \u2013 thanks to JUNCKER |url=https://www.express.co.uk/news/politics/862560/Boris-johnson-dad-Stanley-Johnson-Eu-brexit-news-latest-Jean-Claude-Juncker |newspaper=[[Daily Express]] |access-date=19 January 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2017, Johnson was confirmed as a contestant for the [[I'm a Celebrity...Get Me Out of Here! (UK series 17)|seventeenth series]] of ''[[I'm a Celebrity...Get Me Out of Here! (UK TV series)|I'm a Celebrity...Get Me Out of Here!]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.itv.com/imacelebrity/celebrities/meet-your-2017-celebrity-campmates |title=Meet your 2017 Celebrity Campmates! |publisher=[[ITV (TV network)|ITV]] |date=14 November 2017 |access-date=14 November 2017}}</ref> He was the fifth person to be eliminated from the show, finishing in seventh place.\n\nIn 2018, alongside eight other celebrities, he appeared on the BBC programme ''[[The Real Marigold Hotel]]''.\n\nJohnson said his son [[Boris Johnson]]'s comments that Muslim women who wear burkas look like \"letterboxes\" and \"bank robbers\" did not go far enough and that criticism of the comments had been \"synthetic indignation\" created by political opponents of Boris.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Murphy |first1=Joe |title=Boris Johnson's family at war as his brother raps 'bigotry' of burka jibes |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/politics/boris-johnsons-family-at-war-as-his-brother-raps-bigotry-of-burka-jibes-a3911186.html |accessdate=20 August 2018 |work=Evening Standard |date=14 August 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2018 Johnson said that, irrespective of the solution for the border on the island of Ireland after [[Brexit]], if the Irish people \"want to shoot each other, they will shoot each other\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.belfasttelegraph.co.uk/news/uk/irish-will-shoot-each-other-if-they-want-to-says-stanley-johnson-37426857.html|title=Irish will shoot each other 'if they want to,' says Stanley Johnson|publisher=|accessdate=13 June 2019|via=www.belfasttelegraph.co.uk}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nJohnson married the painter [[Charlotte Johnson Wahl|Charlotte Fawcett]] in [[Marylebone]] in 1963, with whom he had four children: Boris, [[Leader of the Conservative Party (UK)|Leader of the Conservative Party]] and [[Prime Minister of the United Kingdom]], Conservative MP for [[Uxbridge and South Ruislip (UK Parliament constituency)|Uxbridge and South Ruislip]], previously [[Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs|Foreign Secretary]] and [[Mayor of London]]; [[Rachel Johnson|Rachel]], journalist and former editor-in-chief of ''[[The Lady (magazine)|The Lady]]''; [[Jo Johnson|Jo]], Conservative MP for [[Orpington (UK Parliament constituency)|Orpington]], former [[Department for Education|Minister of State for Universities]] and former Head of the [[Lex Column]] at the ''[[Financial Times]]''; and Leo, film-maker and entrepreneur. Johnson and Fawcett divorced in 1979. He married Jennifer Kidd in [[Westminster]] in 1981 and they had two children, Julia and Maximilian.<ref>{{cite news |last=Walden |first=Celia |author-link=Celia Walden |date=11 April 2008 |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/features/3636228/Stanley-Johnson-The-man-who-made-Boris.html |title=Stanley Johnson: The man who made Boris |newspaper=The Daily Telegraph |accessdate=5 July 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Killen |first=Mary |date=March 2015 |title=Boris Johnson's mother on her brilliant brood |url=http://www.tatler.com/article/boris-johnson-family-charlotte-johnson-wahl |newspaper=[[Tatler]] |access-date=19 January 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.freebmd.org.uk/cgi/information.pl?cite=eRsWjz4bnayc0H61aENaeQ&scan=1 |title=Index entry |accessdate=19 January 2018 |work=[[FreeBMD]] |publisher=[[Office for National Statistics]]}}</ref>\n\nAs revealed in 2020, he will apply for [[French citizenship]] once Brexit is done.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.euronews.com/2020/03/22/boris-johnson-s-father-to-apply-for-french-citizenship|website=[[Euronews]]|title=Boris Johnson's father to apply for French citizenship|first=July|last=Gaubert|date=22 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Works==\n*''Gold Drain'' (1967, Heinemann) ISBN B0000CNKG6\n*''Panther Jones for President'' (1968, Heinemann) {{ISBN|0-434-37701-5}}\n*''Life without Birth: A Journey Through the Third World in Search of the Population Explosion'' (1970, Heinemann) {{ISBN|0-434-37702-3}}\n*''The Green Revolution'' (1972, Hamilton) {{ISBN|0-241-02102-2}}\n*''The Population Problem'' (1973, David & C) {{ISBN|0-7153-6282-8}}\n*''The Politics of Environment'' (1973, T Stacey) {{ISBN|0-85468-298-8}}\n*''The Urbane Guerilla'' (1975, Macmillan) {{ISBN|0-333-17679-0}}\n*''Pollution Control Policy of the EEC'' (1978, Graham & Trotman) {{ISBN|0-86010-136-3}}\n*''The Doomsday Deposit'' (1979, EP Dutton) {{ISBN|0-525-09468-7}}\n*''The Marburg Virus'' (1982, Heinemann) {{ISBN|0-434-37704-X}}\n*''Tunnel'' (1984, Heinemann) {{ISBN|0-434-37705-8}}\n*''Antarctica: The Last Great Wilderness'' (1985, Weidenfeld & N) {{ISBN|0-297-78676-8}}\n*''The Commissioner'' (1987, Century) {{ISBN|0-7126-1587-3}}\n*''World Population and the United Nations'' (1987, Cambridge UP) {{ISBN|0-521-32207-3}}\n*''Dragon River'' (1989, Frederick Muller) {{ISBN|0-09-173526-2}}\n*''The Earth Summit: The United Nations Conference on Environment and Development (UNCED)'' (1993, Kluwer Law International) {{ISBN|978-1-85333-784-0}}\n*''World Population - Turning the Tide'' (1994, Kluwer Law International) {{ISBN|1-85966-046-0}}\n*''The Environmental Policy of the European Communities'' (1995, Kluwer Law International) {{ISBN|90-411-0862-9}}\n*''The Politics of Population: Cairo, 1994'' (1995, Earthscan) {{ISBN|1-85383-297-9}}\n*''Icecap'' (1999, Cameron May) {{ISBN|1-874698-67-8}}\n*''Stanley I Presume'' (2009, Fourth Estate Ltd) {{ISBN|0-00-729672-X}}\n*''Survival: Saving Endangered Migratory Species'' [co-authored with Robert Vagg] (2010, Stacey International) {{ISBN|1-906768-11-0}}\n*''Where the Wild Things Were: Travels of a Conservationist'' (2012, Stacey International) {{ISBN|1-906768-87-0}}\n*''UNEP The First 40 Years; A Narrative by Stanley Johnson'' (2012, United Nations Environment Programme) {{ISBN|978-92-807-3314-3}}\n*''Stanley I Resume'' (2014, Biteback) {{ISBN|978-1-84954-741-3}}\n*''Kompromat'' (2017, Point Blank) {{ISBN|978-1-78607-246-7}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.stanleyjohnson.org/ Stanley Johnson] personal site\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070704005109/http://orgclassic.eea.europa.eu/news/Ann1096279340/cv_StanleyJohnson Biographical Note], [[European Environment Agency]]\n*[http://www.channel4.com/news/microsites/E/election2005_blogs/johnson_blog.html Channel 4 Election Weblogs - Stanley Johnson]\n*[http://politics.guardian.co.uk/election/comment/0,15803,1492385,00.html ''The Guardian ruined my political career!''] Stanley Johnson's column 26 May 2005.\n*[http://www.journalisted.com/stanley-johnson Newspaper articles by Stanley Johnson]\n*[http://archives.eui.eu/en/files/transcript/16515.pdf Interview with Stanley Johnson, London 2011, for History of the European Commission (1973-86)]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|eu}}\n{{s-new|constituency}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Member of the European Parliament]]<br>for [[Wight and Hampshire East (European Parliament constituency)|Wight and Hampshire East]]|years=[[1979 European Parliament election in the United Kingdom|1979]]\u2013[[1984 European Parliament election in the United Kingdom|1984]]}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Richard Simmonds]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Boris Johnson}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Johnson, Stanley Patrick}}\n[[Category:1940 births]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Exeter College, Oxford]]\n[[Category:Conservative Party (UK) MEPs]]\n[[Category:Conservative Party (UK) parliamentary candidates]]\n[[Category:English people of Circassian descent]]\n[[Category:English people of French descent]]\n[[Category:English people of German descent]]\n[[Category:English people of Turkish descent]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Members of the European Parliament for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:MEPs for the United Kingdom 1979\u20131984]]\n[[Category:People educated at Sherborne School]]\n[[Category:People from Penzance]]\n[[Category:British politicians of Turkish descent]]\n[[Category:English people of Swiss descent]]\n[[Category:Parents of Prime Ministers of the United Kingdom]]\n", "text_old": "{{other people|Stanley Johnson}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2018}}\n{{Use British English|date=February 2015}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name        = Stanley Johnson\n|image       = Stanleyjohnson.jpg\n|office      = [[Member of the European Parliament]]<br>for [[Wight and Hampshire East (European Parliament constituency)|Wight and Hampshire East]]\n|term_start  = 7 June 1979\n|term_end    = 14 June 1984\n|predecessor = Constituency established\n|successor   = [[Richard Simmonds]]\n|birth_name  = Stanley Patrick Johnson\n|birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1940|8|18|df=y}}\n|birth_place = [[Penzance]], [[Cornwall]], England\n|death_date  = \n|death_place = \n|party       = [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]]\n|spouse      = {{Unbulleted list|{{marriage|[[Charlotte Johnson Wahl|Charlotte Fawcett]]<br>|1963|1979|end=div}}|{{marriage|Jennifer Kidd<br>|1981}}}}\n|children    = {{hlist|[[Boris Johnson|Boris]]|[[Rachel Johnson|Rachel]]|Leo|[[Jo Johnson|Jo]]|Julia|Maximilian}}\n|relatives   = [[Ali Kemal]] (grandfather)\n|alma_mater  = [[Exeter College, Oxford]]\n|module      = {{Listen\n|embed       = yes\n|title       = Johnson's voice \n|filename    = Stanley Johnson - Profile - 4 August 2012.flac\n|type        = speech\n|description = ''[[Desert Island Discs]]'', 18 May 2008 from the BBC programme Profile, 4 August 2012<ref name=\"BBC-b01ldg65\">{{cite episode |title=Stanley Johnson |series=Profile |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b01ldg65 |accessdate=18 January 2014 |station=BBC Radio 4 |date=4 August 2012}}</ref>}}\n}}\n'''Stanley Patrick Johnson''' (born 18 August 1940) is a [[United Kingdom|British]] author<ref>{{cite news |title=Family of influence behind Boris Johnson |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/london-mayor-election/mayor-of-london/1924866/London-mayor-elections-2008-Family-of-influence-behind-Boris-Johnson.html |accessdate=23 July 2019 |publisher=UK Daily Telegraph |date=3 May 2008}}</ref> and former politician. He is also the father of the current British Prime Minster [[Boris Johnson]]. He has written books on environmental and population issues. He was a [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] [[Member of the European Parliament|MEP]] for [[Wight and Hampshire East (European Parliament constituency)|Wight and Hampshire East]] from 1979 to 1984 and is a former employee of the [[World Bank]] and the [[European Commission]].\n\nHis six children include [[Boris Johnson]], who is the [[Leader of the Conservative Party (UK)|Leader of the Conservative Party]] and [[Prime Minister of the United Kingdom]], and former [[Mayor of London]]; [[Jo Johnson]], former MP for [[Orpington (UK Parliament constituency)|Orpington]] and Minister of State for Universities, Science, Research and Innovation; and [[Rachel Johnson]], an editor, journalist, television presenter and author.\n\n==Origins and early life==\nStanley Johnson was born in 1940 in [[Penzance]], Cornwall, the son of Osman Kemal (later Wilfred Johnson) and Irene Williams (daughter of Stanley Fred Williams of [[Bromley]], [[Kent]], and Marie Louise [[Pfeffel family|de Pfeffel]]).<ref>\"Deaths\", ''[[The Times]]'', p. 1, 1 December 1944.</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/world/europe/istanbul-letter-lunch-with-boris-johnson-s-turkish-cousin-1.2650967 |title=Istanbul Letter: Lunch with Boris Johnson\u2019s Turkish cousin |first=Lorraine Mallinder in |last=Istanbul |website=The Irish Times |accessdate=13 June 2019}}</ref> His paternal grandfather, [[Ali Kemal]] Bey, one of the last interior ministers of the [[Ottoman Empire]] government, was assassinated in 1922 during the [[Turkish War of Independence]]. Stanley's father was born in 1909 in [[Bournemouth]], in Hampshire, and his birth was registered as Osman Ali Wilfred Kemal.<ref>Register of Births for the Christchurch Registration District, volume 2b (Dec 1909), p. 621: \"KEMAL, Osman Wilfred\"</ref> Osman's Anglo-Swiss mother Winifred Brun died shortly after giving birth.<ref>Register of Deaths for the Christchurch Registration District, volume 2b (Dec 1909), p. 417: \"KEMAL, Winifred\"</ref> Ali Kemal returned to [[Turkey]] in 1912, whereafter Osman Wilfred and his sister Selma were brought up by their English grandmother, Margaret Brun, and took her maiden name, Johnson, Stanley's father therefore becoming simply Wilfred Johnson.<ref>{{cite web |title=Istanbul Letter: Lunch with Boris Johnson's Turkish cousin |url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/world/europe/istanbul-letter-lunch-with-boris-johnson-s-turkish-cousin-1.2650967 |year=2016 |newspaper=The Irish Times}}</ref>\n\nStanley Johnson's maternal grandmother's parents were Hubert [[Freiherr]] von Pfeffel (born in [[Munich]] on 8 December 1843) and his wife H\u00e9l\u00e8ne [[Jules Arnous de Rivi\u00e8re|Arnous-Rivi\u00e8re]] (born on 14 January 1862). Hubert von Pfeffel was the son of Karl Freiherr von Pfeffel (born in [[Dresden]] on 22 November 1811; died in Munich on 25 January 1890) by his marriage in [[Augsburg]] on 16 February 1836 to Karolina von Rothenburg (born in [[Frankfurt]] on 28 November 1805; died in Frankfurt on 13 February 1872), herself said to be the [[Legitimacy (family law)|illegitimate]], natural daughter of [[Prince Paul of W\u00fcrttemberg]] by Friederike Porth.\n\nJohnson attended [[Sherborne School]], Dorset. While still an undergraduate reading [[Literae Humaniores|Greats]] at [[Exeter College, Oxford|Exeter College]], [[Oxford University|Oxford]], he took part in the Marco Polo Expedition with [[Tim Severin]] and [[Michael de Larrabeiti]], travelling on a motorcycle and sidecar from [[Oxford]] to [[Venice]] and on to India and Afghanistan. The adventure led to the publication of Severin's 1964 book ''Tracking Marco Polo'', with photographs by de Larrabeiti.\n\n==Work and interests==\nHe has previously worked at the [[World Bank Group|World Bank]], has a great interest in the environment and was the Head of Prevention of Pollution Division at the [[European Commission]] from 1973 to 1979. He is a trustee of the Gorilla Organisation and a board member of [[Plantlife International]]. In 1983 he received the [[RSPCA]] Richard Martin Award for Outstanding Services to animal welfare, and in 1984 he received the [[Greenpeace]] Award for Outstanding Services to the Environment. He is an ambassador for the UNEP [[Convention on the Conservation of Migratory Species of Wild Animals]] based in [[Bonn]], Germany.\n\nHe has published a number of books dealing with environmental issues and nine novels, including ''[[The Commissioner (film)|The Commissioner]]'', which was made into a 1998 film starring [[John Hurt]]. In 1962 he won the [[Newdigate Prize]] for Poetry.\n\n==Recent activities==\nAt the [[2005 United Kingdom general election|2005 general election]], Johnson stood for the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]] in the constituency of [[Teignbridge (UK Parliament constituency)|Teignbridge]]. He came second behind [[Richard Younger-Ross]] of the [[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrats]].\n\nFor a time, starting on 26 May 2005, he wrote a weekly column for the ''G2'' section of ''[[The Guardian]]'', and continues to write for various newspapers and magazines, often on environmental topics (see Stanley Johnson personal site below for details). He was one of the first regular hosts of the late night discussion programme ''The Last Word'' on Channel 4's [[More4]] channel, and made an appearance on ''[[Have I Got News For You]]'' on 7 May 2004.{{citation needed|date=March 2018}}\n\nOn 5 May 2008, it was reported that Johnson hoped to be selected to contest his son [[Boris Johnson|Boris]]'s parliamentary seat of [[Henley (UK Parliament constituency)|Henley]] for the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/pages/live/articles/news/news.html?in_article_id=563847&in_page_id=1770&ct=5 |title=Bank holiday Boris promises to work 'night and day' as father eyes his Commons seat |newspaper=[[Daily Mail]] |date=5 May 2008 |accessdate=5 May 2008}}</ref>{{unreliable source?|date=May 2018}} However, on 29 May it was reported that the local Conservative party had chosen three local people as possible candidates<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/oxfordshire/7425090.stm |title=Johnson's father in election snub |publisher=[[BBC News]] |date=29 May 2008 |accessdate=31 May 2008}}</ref> and on 30 May, local councillor [[John Howell (politician)|John Howell]] was selected to fight the by-election.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/oxfordshire/7428812.stm |title=Tory candidate chosen for Henley |publisher=BBC News |date=30 May 2008 |accessdate=31 May 2008}}</ref>\n\nHe has written a memoir, ''Stanley I Presume'', which was published in March 2009.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.stanleyjohnson.com/books/ |title=Stanley Johnson's website - Books page}}</ref>\n\nHaving supported the Remain campaign during the [[2016 United Kingdom European Union membership referendum|2016 European Union membership referendum]], in October 2017 he came out in support of the United Kingdom leaving the European Union, stating that \"the time has come to bail out\" and cited the approach and attitude of the [[European Commission]] [[President of the European Commission|president]] [[Jean-Claude Juncker]] as a major factor in his change of mind. He added that argument and debate over the length or detail of any transition or implementation period is expected but the ultimate \"end-state\" of the UK leaving the European Union is decided.<ref>{{cite news |last=Perring |first=Rebecca |date=6 October 2017 |title=Boris Johnson\u2019s Remainer dad now backs Brexit \u2013 thanks to JUNCKER |url=https://www.express.co.uk/news/politics/862560/Boris-johnson-dad-Stanley-Johnson-Eu-brexit-news-latest-Jean-Claude-Juncker |newspaper=[[Daily Express]] |access-date=19 January 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2017, Johnson was confirmed as a contestant for the [[I'm a Celebrity...Get Me Out of Here! (UK series 17)|seventeenth series]] of ''[[I'm a Celebrity...Get Me Out of Here! (UK TV series)|I'm a Celebrity...Get Me Out of Here!]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.itv.com/imacelebrity/celebrities/meet-your-2017-celebrity-campmates |title=Meet your 2017 Celebrity Campmates! |publisher=[[ITV (TV network)|ITV]] |date=14 November 2017 |access-date=14 November 2017}}</ref> He was the fifth person to be eliminated from the show, finishing in seventh place.\n\nIn 2018, alongside eight other celebrities, he appeared on the BBC programme ''[[The Real Marigold Hotel]]''.\n\nJohnson said his son [[Boris Johnson]]'s comments that Muslim women who wear burkas look like \"letterboxes\" and \"bank robbers\" did not go far enough and that criticism of the comments had been \"synthetic indignation\" created by political opponents of Boris.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Murphy |first1=Joe |title=Boris Johnson's family at war as his brother raps 'bigotry' of burka jibes |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/politics/boris-johnsons-family-at-war-as-his-brother-raps-bigotry-of-burka-jibes-a3911186.html |accessdate=20 August 2018 |work=Evening Standard |date=14 August 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2018 Johnson said that, irrespective of the solution for the border on the island of Ireland after [[Brexit]], if the Irish people \"want to shoot each other, they will shoot each other\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.belfasttelegraph.co.uk/news/uk/irish-will-shoot-each-other-if-they-want-to-says-stanley-johnson-37426857.html|title=Irish will shoot each other 'if they want to,' says Stanley Johnson|publisher=|accessdate=13 June 2019|via=www.belfasttelegraph.co.uk}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nJohnson married the painter [[Charlotte Johnson Wahl|Charlotte Fawcett]] in [[Marylebone]] in 1963, with whom he had four children: Boris, [[Leader of the Conservative Party (UK)|Leader of the Conservative Party]] and [[Prime Minister of the United Kingdom]], Conservative MP for [[Uxbridge and South Ruislip (UK Parliament constituency)|Uxbridge and South Ruislip]], previously [[Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs|Foreign Secretary]] and [[Mayor of London]]; [[Rachel Johnson|Rachel]], journalist and former editor-in-chief of ''[[The Lady (magazine)|The Lady]]''; [[Jo Johnson|Jo]], Conservative MP for [[Orpington (UK Parliament constituency)|Orpington]], former [[Department for Education|Minister of State for Universities]] and former Head of the [[Lex Column]] at the ''[[Financial Times]]''; and Leo, film-maker and entrepreneur. Johnson and Fawcett divorced in 1979. He married Jennifer Kidd in [[Westminster]] in 1981 and they had two children, Julia and Maximilian.<ref>{{cite news |last=Walden |first=Celia |author-link=Celia Walden |date=11 April 2008 |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/features/3636228/Stanley-Johnson-The-man-who-made-Boris.html |title=Stanley Johnson: The man who made Boris |newspaper=The Daily Telegraph |accessdate=5 July 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Killen |first=Mary |date=March 2015 |title=Boris Johnson's mother on her brilliant brood |url=http://www.tatler.com/article/boris-johnson-family-charlotte-johnson-wahl |newspaper=[[Tatler]] |access-date=19 January 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.freebmd.org.uk/cgi/information.pl?cite=eRsWjz4bnayc0H61aENaeQ&scan=1 |title=Index entry |accessdate=19 January 2018 |work=[[FreeBMD]] |publisher=[[Office for National Statistics]]}}</ref>\n\nAs revealed in 2020, he will apply for [[French citizenship]] once Brexit is done.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.euronews.com/2020/03/22/boris-johnson-s-father-to-apply-for-french-citizenship|website=[[Euronews]]|title=Boris Johnson's father to apply for French citizenship|first=July|last=Gaubert|date=22 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Works==\n*''Gold Drain'' (1967, Heinemann) ISBN B0000CNKG6\n*''Panther Jones for President'' (1968, Heinemann) {{ISBN|0-434-37701-5}}\n*''Life without Birth: A Journey Through the Third World in Search of the Population Explosion'' (1970, Heinemann) {{ISBN|0-434-37702-3}}\n*''The Green Revolution'' (1972, Hamilton) {{ISBN|0-241-02102-2}}\n*''The Population Problem'' (1973, David & C) {{ISBN|0-7153-6282-8}}\n*''The Politics of Environment'' (1973, T Stacey) {{ISBN|0-85468-298-8}}\n*''The Urbane Guerilla'' (1975, Macmillan) {{ISBN|0-333-17679-0}}\n*''Pollution Control Policy of the EEC'' (1978, Graham & Trotman) {{ISBN|0-86010-136-3}}\n*''The Doomsday Deposit'' (1979, EP Dutton) {{ISBN|0-525-09468-7}}\n*''The Marburg Virus'' (1982, Heinemann) {{ISBN|0-434-37704-X}}\n*''Tunnel'' (1984, Heinemann) {{ISBN|0-434-37705-8}}\n*''Antarctica: The Last Great Wilderness'' (1985, Weidenfeld & N) {{ISBN|0-297-78676-8}}\n*''The Commissioner'' (1987, Century) {{ISBN|0-7126-1587-3}}\n*''World Population and the United Nations'' (1987, Cambridge UP) {{ISBN|0-521-32207-3}}\n*''Dragon River'' (1989, Frederick Muller) {{ISBN|0-09-173526-2}}\n*''The Earth Summit: The United Nations Conference on Environment and Development (UNCED)'' (1993, Kluwer Law International) {{ISBN|978-1-85333-784-0}}\n*''World Population - Turning the Tide'' (1994, Kluwer Law International) {{ISBN|1-85966-046-0}}\n*''The Environmental Policy of the European Communities'' (1995, Kluwer Law International) {{ISBN|90-411-0862-9}}\n*''The Politics of Population: Cairo, 1994'' (1995, Earthscan) {{ISBN|1-85383-297-9}}\n*''Icecap'' (1999, Cameron May) {{ISBN|1-874698-67-8}}\n*''Stanley I Presume'' (2009, Fourth Estate Ltd) {{ISBN|0-00-729672-X}}\n*''Survival: Saving Endangered Migratory Species'' [co-authored with Robert Vagg] (2010, Stacey International) {{ISBN|1-906768-11-0}}\n*''Where the Wild Things Were: Travels of a Conservationist'' (2012, Stacey International) {{ISBN|1-906768-87-0}}\n*''UNEP The First 40 Years; A Narrative by Stanley Johnson'' (2012, United Nations Environment Programme) {{ISBN|978-92-807-3314-3}}\n*''Stanley I Resume'' (2014, Biteback) {{ISBN|978-1-84954-741-3}}\n*''Kompromat'' (2017, Point Blank) {{ISBN|978-1-78607-246-7}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.stanleyjohnson.org/ Stanley Johnson] personal site\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070704005109/http://orgclassic.eea.europa.eu/news/Ann1096279340/cv_StanleyJohnson Biographical Note], [[European Environment Agency]]\n*[http://www.channel4.com/news/microsites/E/election2005_blogs/johnson_blog.html Channel 4 Election Weblogs - Stanley Johnson]\n*[http://politics.guardian.co.uk/election/comment/0,15803,1492385,00.html ''The Guardian ruined my political career!''] Stanley Johnson's column 26 May 2005.\n*[http://www.journalisted.com/stanley-johnson Newspaper articles by Stanley Johnson]\n*[http://archives.eui.eu/en/files/transcript/16515.pdf Interview with Stanley Johnson, London 2011, for History of the European Commission (1973-86)]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|eu}}\n{{s-new|constituency}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Member of the European Parliament]]<br>for [[Wight and Hampshire East (European Parliament constituency)|Wight and Hampshire East]]|years=[[1979 European Parliament election in the United Kingdom|1979]]\u2013[[1984 European Parliament election in the United Kingdom|1984]]}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Richard Simmonds]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Boris Johnson}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Johnson, Stanley Patrick}}\n[[Category:1940 births]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Exeter College, Oxford]]\n[[Category:Conservative Party (UK) MEPs]]\n[[Category:Conservative Party (UK) parliamentary candidates]]\n[[Category:English people of Circassian descent]]\n[[Category:English people of French descent]]\n[[Category:English people of German descent]]\n[[Category:English people of Turkish descent]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Members of the European Parliament for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:MEPs for the United Kingdom 1979\u20131984]]\n[[Category:People educated at Sherborne School]]\n[[Category:People from Penzance]]\n[[Category:British politicians of Turkish descent]]\n[[Category:English people of Swiss descent]]\n[[Category:Parents of Prime Ministers of the United Kingdom]]\n", "name_user": "WereSpielChequers", "label": "safe", "comment": "secularisation in action", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stanley_Johnson_(writer)"}
{"title_page": "Monophysitism", "text_new": "{{More citations needed|date=April 2020}}\n{{Christology}}\n'''Monophysitism''' ({{IPAc-en|m|\u0259|\u02c8|n|\u0252|f|\u026a|s|a\u026a|\u02cc|t|\u026a|z|\u0259m}} or {{IPAc-en|m|\u0259|\u02c8|n|\u0252|f|\u026a|s|\u026a|\u02cc|t|\u026a|z|\u0259m}}; {{lang-el|\u03bc\u03bf\u03bd\u03bf\u03c6\u03c5\u03c3\u03b9\u03c4\u03b9\u03c3\u03bc\u03cc\u03c2}}; [[Koine Greek phonology|Late Koine Greek]], {{IPA-el|monofysitiz\u02c8mos|pron}} from \u03bc\u03cc\u03bd\u03bf\u03c2 ''monos'', \"single\" and \u03c6\u03cd\u03c3\u03b9\u03c2 ''physis'', \"nature\") is the [[Christology|Christological]] position that Jesus Christ has a '' single'' \"nature\", rather than being both divine and human. Monophysitism is used as a way of describing Eutychianism.{{Citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\nMonophysitism considers any Christology which somehow joins the divine nature to a created human nature as equivalent to [[Nestorianism|Nestorian]] [[Adoptionism]] which arose from the [[School of Antioch]]. Monophysitism was represented by groups such as the [[Agnoetae]]. Monophysite heresies include [[Tritheism]], [[Sabellianism]], [[Docetism]] and [[Julianism]].{{Citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\nMonophysitism is not to be confused with [[Miaphysitism]], the belief of the [[Oriental Orthodox]] Churches.{{Citation needed|date=April 2020}} \n\n\n==Emperors who favoured Monophysitism==\nEmperor [[Basiliscus]] brought the Monophysites to the pinnicle of their power.<ref>\"The Church Triumphant: A History of Christianity Up to 1300\" E. Glenn Hinson, p. 254</ref> His [[Encyclion]]{{Citation needed|date=April 2020}} condemned Eutyches and it condemned Chalcedon. \n\nEmperor [[Zeno (emperor)|Zeno]] was a Monophysite{{Citation needed|date=April 2020}} whose [[Henoticon]] condemned Eutyches and undid Chalcedon. \n\nEmperor [[Anastasius I Dicorus]] was a supporter of Monophysitism without Eutyches. <ref>\"History and Heresy: How Historical Forces Can Create Doctrinal Conflicts\" Joseph F. Kelly, p.71</ref>\n\nEmperor [[Justin II]] and [[Sophia (empress)|Sophia]] were for a long time ardent Monophysites excluding Eutyches. <ref>Byzantium and the Arabs in the Sixth Century\" Irfan Shahid</ref>\n\n==Eutyches and Monophysitism==\nIn opposition to [[Nestorius]] who denied the hypostatic union of the Divine and human natures of Christ,<ref>http://www.oxfordreference.com/view/10.1093/acref/9780198614425.001.0001/acref-9780198614425-e-4020</ref> [[Cyril of Alexandria]] articulated the Christological formula \"Mia physis tou theou logou sesarkomene\"<ref>https://classicalchristianity.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/05/St.-Cyril-of-Alexandria\u2019s-Miaphysite-Christology-and-Chalcedonian-Dyophysitism.pdf</ref> which is to say that Christ is fully Divine and fully human but that there is only one compound (Mia) physis (nature), which is to be understood as the the Incarnation of God the Son. <ref>https://www.ukmidcopts.org/kotob/on_the_unity_of_Christ_st_cyril.pdf</ref> The formula was accepted by the worldwide church. \n\nA priest named [[Eutyches]] emerged after Cyril's death to further oppose Nestorianism but in doing so insisted more clearly that Christ's divine nature absorbs the human nature leaving only one nature like a drop into the ocean (essentially divine)<ref>https://ccel.org/ccel/wace/biodict.html?\\\\\\term=Eutyches%20and%20Eutychianism</ref>. Eutychianism has been described as \"an extreme form of the Monophysite heresy that emphasizes the exclusive prevalence of the divinity in Christ\".<ref>https://www.britannica.com/biography/Eutyches</ref>\n\nThis Eutychian view of only one simple (mono) nature of Christ, became a major controversy in the Church resulting in worldwide resistance and later excommunication of Eutyches <ref>https://www.ccel.org/ccel/wace/biodict.html?term=Dioscorus%20(1),%20patriarch%20of%20Alexandria</ref>{{Verify source|date=April 2020}}<!--How could any such idea have become \"worldwide\" at that time?--> Later, in the Council of Chalcedon of 451 A.D., [[Pope Dioscorus I of Alexandria]] among others, condemned the teachings of Eutyches and of monophysitism. \n\nDespite the worldwide church condemning Eutyches, the Church divided into Chalcedonians and Non-Chalcedonians for other reasons.<ref>https://ccel.org/ccel/schaff/npnf214/npnf214.xi.x.html</ref> It is commonly misconceived that this was due to Non-Chalcedonians being monophysites.<ref>http://orthodoxinfo.com/ecumenism/ea_mono.aspx</ref>\n\n==Oriental Orthodox Rejection of Monophysitism==\nWhilst it has been clear the Chalcedonian Churches reject Monophysitism, there has been continued confusion over the view of the Oriental Orthodox Churches. Chalcedonians such as the [[Eastern Orthodox]] have often labelled Dioscorus (and all Oriental Orthodox) as monophysites and therefore heretics, <ref>http://orthodoxinfo.com/ecumenism/copts_orth.aspx</ref> most likely due to their effort{{Citation needed|date=April 2020}} to rehabilitate Eutyches (which failed). However, this is strongly refuted by the [[Oriental Orthodox]] who prefer to be labelled [[Miaphysites]]. The liturgical prayers of [[Basil of Caesarea]] used by the [[Oriental Orthodox]] Churches to this day affirm their miaphysitism and objection to both [[Arianism]] and Monophysitism.<ref>https://www.copticchurch.net/topics/liturgy/liturgy_of_st_basil.pdf</ref><ref>https://ukmidcopts.org/coptic/universal/</ref> \n\nIn 1973, the [[Coptic Orthodox]] and [[Roman Catholic]] Popes signed a common declaration on Christology. This was the first modern era official recognition by a Chalcedonian church that Oriental Orthodox Churches are not Monophysites.<ref>http://www.vatican.va/roman_curia/pontifical_councils/chrstuni/anc-orient-ch-docs/rc_pc_christuni_doc_19730510_copti_en.html</ref>\n\nTherefore Western Catholics{{Failed verification|date=April 2020}} avoid referring to Non-Chalcedonians as Monophysites. For example the definition in The Oxford Dictionary of Late Antiquity, p. 1016 reads: \"Though the term 'Monophysite' occurs in dogmatic discussions of Miaphysitism from the 7th century onwards, it is technically inaccurate, being a heresiological label properly confined to the view in which the union of divine and human in Christ is seen to result either in the emergence of a distinct 'third' nature or the absorption of one nature into the other (usually the human into the divine) as in the profession of Eutyches (d. c. 554), whose emphasis on the singularity of Christ's incarnate nature appears to have led him to deny that Christ's body was consubstantial to human flesh.\"\n\nThe Eastern Orthodox came to a Christological agreement with the Oriental Orthodox in this same area in September 1990 <ref>https://www.trinityorthodox.ca/sites/default/files/Agreed%20Statements-Orthodox-Oriental%20Orthodox%20Dialogue-1989-1990.pdf</ref>.\n\nThe Anglican Communion similarly signed a statement in October 2014 affirming the Oriental Orthodox rejection of monophysitism and the adoption of the Christological [[Miaphysitism|Miaphysis]] formula of [[Cyril of Alexandria]] <ref>http://www.anglicancommunion.org/media/103502/anglican-oriental-orthodox-agreed-statement-on-christology-cairo-2014.pdf</ref>.\n\n==Citations==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Christian theology}}\n{{Heresies condemned by the Catholic Church}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Christian terminology]]\n[[Category:Christianity in the Byzantine Empire]]\n[[Category:Christianity in the Middle East]]\n[[Category:Christology]]\n[[Category:Heresy in Christianity]]\n[[Category:Schisms in Christianity]]\n\n{{Christianity-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{More citations needed|date=April 2020}}\n{{Christology}}\n'''Monophysitism''' ({{IPAc-en|m|\u0259|\u02c8|n|\u0252|f|\u026a|s|a\u026a|\u02cc|t|\u026a|z|\u0259m}} or {{IPAc-en|m|\u0259|\u02c8|n|\u0252|f|\u026a|s|\u026a|\u02cc|t|\u026a|z|\u0259m}}; {{lang-el|\u03bc\u03bf\u03bd\u03bf\u03c6\u03c5\u03c3\u03b9\u03c4\u03b9\u03c3\u03bc\u03cc\u03c2}}; [[Koine Greek phonology|Late Koine Greek]], {{IPA-el|monofysitiz\u02c8mos|pron}} from \u03bc\u03cc\u03bd\u03bf\u03c2 ''monos'', \"single\" and \u03c6\u03cd\u03c3\u03b9\u03c2 ''physis'', \"nature\") is the [[Christology|Christological]] position that Jesus Christ has a '' single'' \"nature\", rather than being both divine and human. Monophysitism is used as a way of describing Eutychianism.{{Citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\nMonophysitism considers any Christology which somehow joins the divine nature to a created human nature as equivalent to [[Nestorianism|Nestorian]] [[Adoptionism]] which arose from the [[School of Antioch]]. Monophysitism was represented by groups such as the [[Agnoetae]]. Monophysite heresies include [[Tritheism]], [[Sabellianism]], [[Docetism]] and [[Julianism]].{{Citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\nMonophysitism is not to be confused with [[Miaphysitism]], the belief of the [[Oriental Orthodox]] Churches.{{Citation needed|date=April 2020}} \n\n\n==Emperors who favoured Monophysitism==\nEmperor [[Basiliscus]] brought the Monophysites to the pinnicle of their power.<ref>\"The Church Triumphant: A History of Christianity Up to 1300\" E. Glenn Hinson, p. 254</ref> His [[Encyclion]]{{Citation needed|date=April 2020}} condemned Eutyches and it condemned Chalcedon. \n\nEmperor [[Zeno (emperor)|Zeno]] was a Monophysite{{Citation needed|date=April 2020}} whose [[Henoticon]] condemned Eutyches and undid Chalcedon. \n\nEmperor [[Anastasius I Dicorus]] was a supporter of Monophysitism without Eutyches. <ref>\"History and Heresy: How Historical Forces Can Create Doctrinal Conflicts\" Joseph F. Kelly, p.71</ref>\n\nEmperor [[Justin II]] and [[Sophia (empress)|Sophia]] were for a long time ardent Monophysites excluding Eutyches. <ref>Byzantium and the Arabs in the Sixth Century\" Irfan Shahid</ref>\n\n==Eutyches and Monophysitism==\nIn opposition to [[Nestorius]] who denied the hypostatic union of the Divine and human natures of Christ,<ref>http://www.oxfordreference.com/view/10.1093/acref/9780198614425.001.0001/acref-9780198614425-e-4020</ref> [[Cyril of Alexandria]] articulated the Christological formula \"Mia physis tou theou logou sesarkomene\"<ref>https://classicalchristianity.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/05/St.-Cyril-of-Alexandria\u2019s-Miaphysite-Christology-and-Chalcedonian-Dyophysitism.pdf</ref> which is to say that Christ is fully Divine and fully human but that there is only one compound (Mia) physis (nature), which is to be understood as the the Incarnation of God the Son. <ref>https://www.ukmidcopts.org/kotob/on_the_unity_of_Christ_st_cyril.pdf</ref> The formula was accepted by the worldwide church. \n\nA priest named [[Eutyches]] emerged after Cyril's death to further oppose Nestorianism but in doing so insisted more clearly that Christ's divine nature absorbs the human nature leaving only one nature like a drop into the ocean (essentially divine)<ref>https://ccel.org/ccel/wace/biodict.html?\\\\\\term=Eutyches%20and%20Eutychianism</ref>. Eutychianism has been described as \"an extreme form of the Monophysite heresy that emphasizes the exclusive prevalence of the divinity in Christ\".<ref>https://www.britannica.com/biography/Eutyches</ref>\n\nThis Eutychian view of only one simple (mono) nature of Christ, became a major controversy in the Church resulting in worldwide resistance and later excommunication of Eutyches <ref>https://www.ccel.org/ccel/wace/biodict.html?term=Dioscorus%20(1),%20patriarch%20of%20Alexandria</ref>{{Verify source|date=April 2020}}<!--How could any such idea have become \"worldwide\" at that time?--> Later, in the Council of Chalcedon of 451 A.D., [[Pope Dioscorus I of Alexandria]] among others, condemned the teachings of Eutyches and of monophysitism. \n\nDespite the worldwide church condemning Eutyches, the Church divided into Chalcedonians and Non-Chalcedonians for other reasons.<ref>https://ccel.org/ccel/schaff/npnf214/npnf214.xi.x.html</ref> It is commonly reported that this was due to Non-Chalcedonians being Monophysitism.{{Citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\n==Oriental Orthodox Rejection of Monophysitism==\nWhilst it has been clear the Chalcedonian Churches reject Monophysitism, there has been continued confusion over the view of the Oriental Orthodox Churches. Chalcedonians such as the [[Eastern Orthodox]] have often labelled Dioscorus (and all Oriental Orthodox) as monophysites and therefore heretics, <ref>http://orthodoxinfo.com/ecumenism/copts_orth.aspx</ref> most likely due to their effort{{Citation needed|date=April 2020}} to rehabilitate Eutyches (which failed). However, this is strongly refuted by the [[Oriental Orthodox]] who prefer to be labelled [[Miaphysites]]. The liturgical prayers of [[Basil of Caesarea]] used by the [[Oriental Orthodox]] Churches to this day affirm their miaphysitism and objection to both [[Arianism]] and Monophysitism.<ref>https://www.copticchurch.net/topics/liturgy/liturgy_of_st_basil.pdf</ref><ref>https://ukmidcopts.org/coptic/universal/</ref> \n\nIn 1973, the [[Coptic Orthodox]] and [[Roman Catholic]] Popes signed a common declaration on Christology. This was the first modern era official recognition by a Chalcedonian church that Oriental Orthodox Churches are not Monophysites.<ref>http://www.vatican.va/roman_curia/pontifical_councils/chrstuni/anc-orient-ch-docs/rc_pc_christuni_doc_19730510_copti_en.html</ref>\n\nTherefore Western Catholics{{Failed verification|date=April 2020}} avoid referring to Non-Chalcedonians as Monophysites. For example the definition in The Oxford Dictionary of Late Antiquity, p. 1016 reads: \"Though the term 'Monophysite' occurs in dogmatic discussions of Miaphysitism from the 7th century onwards, it is technically inaccurate, being a heresiological label properly confined to the view in which the union of divine and human in Christ is seen to result either in the emergence of a distinct 'third' nature or the absorption of one nature into the other (usually the human into the divine) as in the profession of Eutyches (d. c. 554), whose emphasis on the singularity of Christ's incarnate nature appears to have led him to deny that Christ's body was consubstantial to human flesh.\"\n\nThe Eastern Orthodox came to a Christological agreement with the Oriental Orthodox in this same area in September 1990 <ref>https://www.trinityorthodox.ca/sites/default/files/Agreed%20Statements-Orthodox-Oriental%20Orthodox%20Dialogue-1989-1990.pdf</ref>.\n\nThe Anglican Communion similarly signed a statement in October 2014 affirming the Oriental Orthodox rejection of monophysitism and the adoption of the Christological [[Miaphysitism|Miaphysis]] formula of [[Cyril of Alexandria]] <ref>http://www.anglicancommunion.org/media/103502/anglican-oriental-orthodox-agreed-statement-on-christology-cairo-2014.pdf</ref>.\n\n==Citations==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Christian theology}}\n{{Heresies condemned by the Catholic Church}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Christian terminology]]\n[[Category:Christianity in the Byzantine Empire]]\n[[Category:Christianity in the Middle East]]\n[[Category:Christology]]\n[[Category:Heresy in Christianity]]\n[[Category:Schisms in Christianity]]\n\n{{Christianity-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Joe9y", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eEutyches and Monophysitism", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Monophysitism"}
{"title_page": "Rokycany, Pre\u0161ov District", "text_new": "{{dablink|For the town in the Czech Republic, see [[Rokycany]].}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n| name                    = Rokycany\n| native_name             = \n| other_name              = \n| settlement_type         = Village\n<!-- images, nickname, motto -->\n| image_skyline           = Slovakia Rokycany 8.JPG\n| image_caption           = \n| image_flag              = \n| image_shield            = \n| motto                   = \n| nickname                = \n| etymology               = \n<!-- location -->\n| subdivision_type        = Country\n| subdivision_name        = Slovakia\n| subdivision_type1       = \n| subdivision_name1       = \n| subdivision_type2       = Region\n| subdivision_name2       = [[Pre\u0161ov Region|Pre\u0161ov]]\n| subdivision_type3       = District\n| subdivision_name3       = [[Pre\u0161ov District|Pre\u0161ov]]\n| subdivision_type4       = \n| subdivision_name4       = \n<!-- maps and coordinates -->\n| image_map               = \n| map_caption             = \n| pushpin_map             = Slovakia\n| pushpin_relief          = \n| pushpin_map_caption     = Location of Rokycany in Slovakia \n| coordinates             = {{coord|48|58|N|21|09|E|display=inline,title}}\n| coordinates_footnotes   = \n<!-- established -->\n| established_title       = \n| established_date        = \n<!-- area -->\n| area_footnotes          = \n| area_total_km2          = 5.79\n| area_total_sq_mi        = \n| area_land_sq_mi         = \n| area_water_sq_mi        = \n<!-- elevation -->\n| elevation_footnotes     = \n| elevation_m             = 331\n| elevation_ft            = \n<!-- population -->\n| population_as_of        = 2004-12-31\n| population_footnotes    = \n| population_total        = 793\n| population_density_km2  = auto\n| population_density_sq_mi=\n| population_demonym      = \n<!-- time zone(s) -->\n| timezone1               = \n| utc_offset1             = \n| timezone1_DST           = \n| utc_offset1_DST         = \n<!-- postal codes, area code -->\n| postal_code_type        = Postal code\n| postal_code             = 082 41\n| area_code_type          =  \n| area_code               = \n| geocode                 = \n| iso_code                = \n| blank_name              = [[Slovak car registration plates|Car plate]]\n| blank_info              = PO\n<!-- website, footnotes -->\n| website                 = \n| footnotes               = \n}}\n'''Rokycany''' ({{lang-rue|\u0420\u043e\u043a\u0456\u0446\u0430\u043d\u0456}}, {{Lang-hu|Berki}}) is a [[village]] in [[Pre\u0161ov District]] in the [[Pre\u0161ov Region]] in East [[Slovakia]].\n\n==History==\nIn [[history|historical records]] the [[village]] was first mentioned in 1295.\n\n==Geography==\nThe [[municipality]] lies at an [[altitude]] of 331 metres and covers an [[area]] of 5.785&nbsp;km\u00b2. It has a [[population]] of about 795 people.\n\n==Notable people==\n[[Hungary|Hungarian]] politician [[J\u00e1nos Gy\u00f6ngy\u00f6si]], who served as [[Minister of Foreign Affairs]] between 1944 and 1947.\n\n==External links==\n\n{{Presov District}}\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rokycany, Presov District}}\n[[Category:Villages and municipalities in Pre\u0161ov District]]\n[[Category:\u0160ari\u0161]]\n\n\n{{Pre\u0161ov-geo-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{dablink|For the town in the Czech Republic, see [[Rokycany]].}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n| name                    = Rokycany\n| native_name             = \n| other_name              = \n| settlement_type         = Village\n<!-- images, nickname, motto -->\n| image_skyline           = Slovakia Rokycany 8.JPG\n| image_caption           = \n| image_flag              = \n| image_shield            = \n| motto                   = \n| nickname                = \n| etymology               = \n<!-- location -->\n| subdivision_type        = Country\n| subdivision_name        = Slovakia\n| subdivision_type1       = \n| subdivision_name1       = \n| subdivision_type2  